         <OBJECT_CONTRACT>
            <TITLE>
               <P>Contract Relating to the Design and Construction of Residential Units at Forty Hill, Holthwhites Hill, Lavender Hill and Jasper Close</P>
            </TITLE>
            <REFERENCE_NUMBER>DN315388</REFERENCE_NUMBER>
            <CPV_MAIN>
               <CPV_CODE CODE="45000000"/>
            </CPV_MAIN>
            <TYPE_CONTRACT CTYPE="WORKS"/>
            <SHORT_DESCR>
               <P>A contract for the completion of part finished projects at 4 sites across the borough, as more particularly described in section 11.2.4 of this notice.</P>
            </SHORT_DESCR>
            <VAL_TOTAL CURRENCY="GBP">10207558</VAL_TOTAL>
            <NO_LOT_DIVISION/>
            <OBJECT_DESCR ITEM="1">
               <n2016:NUTS CODE="UKI"/>
               <MAIN_SITE>
                  <P>Various sites across the London Borough of Enfield.</P>
               </MAIN_SITE>
               <SHORT_DESCR>
                  <P>A contract for the completion of part finished projects at 4 sites in the Borough, being:</P>
                  <P>— Forty Hill — 9 Residential units, constructed on piled foundations using a closed panel timber frame system,</P>
                  <P>— Holtwhites Hill — 9 Residential units, constructed on piled foundations using a closed panel timber frame system on and adjacent to the network rail maintenance access rd,</P>
                  <P>— Lavender Hill — 12 Residential units, constructed on piled foundations using a closed panel timber frame system,</P>
                  <P>— Jasper Close — 18 Residential units, constructed on piled foundations using a closed panel timber frame system.</P>
                  <P>Under the contract (a JCT Design and Build Contract, with amendments), AMCM will be required to continue with the design and manufacture of part completed timber frames from the nominated supplier. AMCM will assume the risk associated with design, ground surveys and part completed works, will issue warranties for works completed to date and afterwards and will ensure all works satisfy building regulations.</P>
               </SHORT_DESCR>
               <AC_COST>
                  <AC_CRITERION>Quality</AC_CRITERION>
                  <AC_WEIGHTING>100</AC_WEIGHTING>
               </AC_COST>
               <NO_OPTIONS/>
               <NO_EU_PROGR_RELATED/>
            </OBJECT_DESCR>
         </OBJECT_CONTRACT>
         <PROCEDURE>
            <PT_AWARD_CONTRACT_WITHOUT_CALL>
               <D_ACCORDANCE_ARTICLE>
                  <D_TECHNICAL/>
               </D_ACCORDANCE_ARTICLE>
               <D_JUSTIFICATION>
                  <P>The London Borough of Enfield (the Council) has awarded the contract to AMCM Group Limited (AMCM) pursuant to Regulation 32(2)(b)(ii) of the Public Contracts Regulations 2015 (the Regulations). For the reasons explained below, the Council is of the view that the contract can only be awarded to AMCM because competition is absent for technical reasons, and no reasonable alternative or substitute exists. In 2015, the Council entered into a development agreement with Kier Investments. These projects included the 4 projects referred to in section 11.2.4 of this notice (the "4 Projects"). Kier appointed AMCM as its contractor for the 4 Projects under a JCT Design and Build Contract, and AMCM commenced works on site in. Following the termination of the development agreement between the Council and Kier in respect of the completion of the 4 projects, the Council has had to assume the role of employer in relation to the 4 Projects and so has entered into a JCT Design and Build Contract directly with AMCM (the Contract) for the completion of the part finished works which are further described in section 11.2.4. The Council has considered the relevant market and is of the view that if it had sought to procure the part finished works covered by the contract by way of an advertised procurement process, competition would have been absent for technical reasons because no contractor in the relevant market other than AMCM would, in practice, have been able to put forward a viable bid that would have met the Council’s lawful requirements. This is because of:</P>
                  <P>1) AMCM's knowledge of the 4 Projects and the works undertaken to date, including the closed panel timber frame system;</P>
                  <P>2) The Council’s requirements for warranties that the works undertaken to date have been carried out to the required standards and in accordance with all applicable building regulations, together with warranties in respect of all design work undertaken to date;</P>
                  <P>3) The requirement for mobilisation, once instructed, within a short period;</P>
                  <P>4) The requirement that the works are to be continued “as is”, without any redoing of previously completed works. The Council considers that it would have been unrealistic to have expected any contractors other than AMCM to provide such warranties and fulfil the Council’s other requirements. The Council also considers that the absence of competition is not the result of an artificial narrowing down of the parameters of the procurement.</P>
               </D_JUSTIFICATION>
            </PT_AWARD_CONTRACT_WITHOUT_CALL>
